const faqs = [
  { q: 'Is a monitor light bar better than a desk lamp?', a: 'For monitor users, yes. A monitor light bar uses an asymmetric lens to direct light at a 45-degree angle onto your desk and keyboard, completely avoiding the monitor surface. This eliminates screen glare, which is the single biggest source of eye strain from desk lamps. A traditional desk lamp bounces light off the screen and creates visible reflections.' },
  { q: 'Does the BenQ ScreenBar Halo auto-dimming actually work?', a: 'Yes, and it is the feature that justifies the price. The Halo has a built-in ambient light sensor that adjusts brightness every few seconds based on room light. In our testing it held desk illumination within 50 lux of our target across 45 nights, dimming automatically when the sun set and brightening when we turned on overhead lights.' },
  { q: 'Can a monitor light bar damage your monitor?', a: 'No. Quality light bars like the BenQ ScreenBar Halo and Baseus use a counterweight clamp that distributes weight evenly across the top of the monitor bezel, not the screen. They attach to bezels 0.4 to 1.1 inches thick. They will not scratch or damage a modern monitor, but check your bezel thickness before buying.' },
