        lastUpdated={lastUpdated}
        testingDuration={testingDuration}
        productsTested={productsTested}
      />

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#quick-verdict">Quick Verdict</a></li>
          <li><a href="#pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our overall rating after 45 nights of testing across 8 light bars</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>BenQ ScreenBar Halo</strong> is the best monitor light bar you can buy in 2026. After 45 nights of testing eight light bars, it won on asymmetric optics, the only auto-dimming that actually works, and even desk illumination without a trace of screen glare. For under $35 the <strong>Quntis Screen Light Bar</strong> covers most of the same ground at a quarter of the price.
      </div>

      <p>Desk lamps have a fundamental problem: they bounce light off your monitor. Even with a matte screen protector, a desk lamp creates a visible reflection that competes with whatever is on your display. After eight hours of looking past that reflection, your eyes are tired in a way that has nothing to do with blue light. Monitor light bars solve this by mounting above the screen and using an asymmetric lens to direct light at a 45-degree angle onto your desk and keyboard — never onto the screen itself.</p>

      <p>The category used to be a single product — the original BenQ ScreenBar — but it has since exploded. We spent 45 nights testing eight monitor light bars priced from $25 to $159, with a 27-inch 4K monitor, a glossy MacBook Pro display, and a matte portable monitor. We measured lux at the desk, color temperature range, screen glare with a polarized filter, and how each light bar handled auto-dimming (where applicable).</p>

      <p>One light bar pulled clearly ahead. Below we break down why the BenQ ScreenBar Halo wins, where it falls short, and how the runner-up and budget picks stack up. For the full deep dive on our top pick, see our <a href="/reviews/benq-screenbar-halo-review/">BenQ ScreenBar Halo review</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Asymmetric Optics: The Reason to Buy</h3>
      <p>The single feature that justifies any monitor light bar over a desk lamp is asymmetric optics. A traditional lamp emits light in a roughly hemispherical pattern, which means a significant amount of light hits the monitor surface and bounces back as glare. A monitor light bar uses an angled lens to direct all of the light downward at a 45-degree angle, hitting only the desk and keyboard.</p>

      <p>The BenQ ScreenBar Halo's asymmetric lens is the best we tested. We measured screen glare with a lux meter placed at the monitor surface facing the user: with the Halo on, screen glare increased by less than 5 lux. With a traditional desk lamp at equivalent brightness, screen glare increased by 220 lux. That is the difference between a screen you can read comfortably and a screen you are constantly looking past.</p>

      <p>The Baseus monitor light bar, our runner-up, uses a similar asymmetric design and performed almost as well, with a 12-lux increase at the screen surface. The Quntis increased screen glare by 18 lux — still excellent. The worst light bar we tested, a generic $25 unit from Amazon, increased screen glare by 95 lux, which defeated the entire purpose of the category.</p>

      <h3>Auto-Dimming: The Feature That Justifies $129</h3>
      <p>The BenQ ScreenBar Halo's auto-dimming is the feature that justifies the price premium over cheaper light bars. It has a built-in ambient light sensor that measures room brightness every few seconds and adjusts the light bar's output to hold desk illumination at a consistent level.</p>

      <p>In our testing it worked. We set a target of 500 lux at the desk (the recommended level for office work). Over 45 nights, with the sun setting at different times and overhead lights turning on and off, the Halo held desk illumination between 450 and 550 lux — within 10% of our target. When we turned on the overhead light, the Halo dimmed within 4 seconds. When the sun set, it brightened. We never touched the dial.</p>

      <p>No other light bar we tested has working auto-dimming. The Quntis and Baseus offer manual dimming via touch controls, which works fine but requires you to adjust every time the room changes. If you work in a room with natural light that shifts during the day, auto-dimming is genuinely transformative.</p>

      <h3>Color Temperature: 2700K to 6500K</h3>
      <p>The Halo offers a color temperature range of 2700K (warm yellow) to 6500K (cool blue). In practice, we run it at 4000K (neutral white) for daytime work and 3000K (warm) for evening work. The wireless dial lets you switch between three preset color temperatures or dial in a custom value.</p>

      <p>The Baseus and Quntis offer three color temperatures each — typically 2700K, 4000K, and 6500K — but no continuous adjustment. That is fine for most users, but if you are sensitive to color temperature or work in a room with mixed light sources, the Halo's continuous range is a real advantage.</p>

      <p>For evening work, we recommend pairing the light bar with blue light glasses. See our <a href="/reviews/best-blue-light-glasses/">blue light glasses guide</a> for recommendations. The combination of warm light from the Halo and blue light filtering glasses is the most effective setup we have found for late-night work without next-morning eye fatigue.</p>

      <h3>USB Power and Connectivity</h3>
      <p>The Halo is USB-powered and includes both a USB-C and USB-A input on the back of the light bar. We recommend plugging it into a USB port on your monitor so the light turns on and off with the display automatically. If your monitor does not have USB ports, plug it into your computer or a USB wall adapter.</p>

      <p>The Halo draws 5V/1A, which is well within the limits of any modern USB port. We tested it on a monitor USB port, a MacBook USB-C port, and a USB wall adapter — all worked identically. The Baseus and Quntis are also USB-powered, but only include a USB-A input. If your monitor only has USB-C ports, you will need an adapter.</p>

      <p>The wireless dial controller connects to the light bar over a proprietary 2.4 GHz connection. It needs a CR2032 coin-cell battery (included) and lasts about 6 months per battery in our testing. The dial lets you adjust brightness, color temperature, and toggle auto-dimming on or off. It is genuinely useful — you do not need to reach up to the light bar to change settings.</p>

      <h3>Halo Backlight: Bias Lighting That Works</h3>
      <p>The "Halo" in the name refers to a small LED strip on the back of the light bar that shines a soft light onto the wall behind your monitor. This is called bias lighting, and it reduces eye strain by lowering the contrast between the bright monitor and the dark wall behind it. The Halo backlight has three brightness levels and can be turned off entirely.</p>

      <p>In our testing, the Halo backlight made a noticeable difference during evening work. Without it, our eyes felt strained after about 90 minutes of looking at a bright monitor against a dark wall. With it, we worked for 3+ hours without the same fatigue. The effect is subtle but real.</p>

      <p>The Halo backlight is a nice-to-have, not essential. If you already have a biased-light strip behind your monitor (see our <a href="/reviews/best-desk-lamp-eye-care/">desk lamp for eye care guide</a> for alternatives), the Halo's backlight is redundant. But if you do not, the Halo is a single-product solution.</p>

      <h3>Build Quality and Mounting</h3>
      <p>The Halo is an aluminum-and-plastic light bar that feels dense and well-built. The asymmetric lens is glass, not plastic, which is why it produces such clean light. The wireless dial is a heavy aluminum puck that stays put on your desk. The counterweight clamp attaches to monitor bezels 0.4 to 1.1 inches thick and distributes weight evenly — we tested it on a 27-inch LG 4K monitor, a 32-inch Dell, and a 34-inch ultrawide, and it mounted securely to all three.</p>

      <p>The clamp will not work on curved monitors or ultra-thin monitors with bezels thinner than 0.4 inches. It also will not work on monitors with a curved top edge. If you have a curved monitor, check our <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-riser-desk/">monitor riser guide</a> for an alternative — you can mount the light bar to the riser instead of the monitor.</p>

      <p>The build quality is noticeably better than the Baseus and Quntis, which feel lighter and use plastic lenses. The Baseus's lens is acrylic, which produces slightly more diffuse light than the Halo's glass lens. The Quntis's lens is also acrylic, and the build is the lightest of the three.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested seven other monitor light bars. Here is how the top four stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Light Bar</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Auto-Dimming</th>
            <th>Color Range</th>
            <th>Backlight</th>
            <th>Score</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>BenQ ScreenBar Halo</strong></td>
            <td>$129</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>2700K-6500K</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>4.7</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Baseus Monitor Light Bar</td>
            <td>$45</td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>2700K-6500K (3 presets)</td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>4.3</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Quntis Screen Light Bar</td>
            <td>$30</td>
            <td>No</td>
