            <td>No</td>
            <td>4.1</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>BenQ ScreenBar (non-Halo)</td>
            <td>$99</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>2700K-6500K</td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>4.5</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Baseus Monitor Light Bar</strong> is our runner-up. At $45 it has asymmetric optics, three color temperature presets, and stepless dimming via touch controls. It lacks auto-dimming and the Halo backlight, and the build quality is lighter. But for the price it is remarkable. If you do not need auto-dimming, the Baseus is the smart pick — it covers 80% of the Halo experience at a third of the price.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Quntis Screen Light Bar</strong> is the budget champion. At $30 it has asymmetric optics, three color temperatures, and stepless dimming. It lacks auto-dimming and the build quality is the lightest of the three. But for under $35 it delivers 70% of the BenQ experience at a quarter of the price. If you are buying light bars for an entire team, this is the smart pick.</p>

      <p>The <strong>BenQ ScreenBar (non-Halo)</strong> is the older model at $99. It has the same asymmetric optics and working auto-dimming as the Halo, but lacks the backlight. If you already have a biased-light strip behind your monitor, the non-Halo ScreenBar is $30 less and just as good.</p>

      <p>Complete your desk setup with proper surface and ergonomics. A <a href="/reviews/best-desk-pad-large/">large desk pad</a> gives the light something to bounce off cleanly, and a <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-riser-desk/">monitor riser</a> raises your monitor so the light bar can mount securely even on curved displays. For the full breakdown on our top pick, see our <a href="/reviews/benq-screenbar-halo-review/">BenQ ScreenBar Halo review</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the BenQ ScreenBar Halo if you work at a monitor past sunset for 4+ hours and your monitor has a flat top bezel between 0.4 and 1.1 inches thick. The auto-dimming alone justifies the price for users in rooms with shifting natural light. At $129 it is not cheap, but it is the only light bar we tested that handled everything we threw at it.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. BenQ runs promotions around Prime Day and Black Friday where the Halo drops to $99 to $109. We have seen it as low as $89 during clearance events. Set a price alert if you are not in a rush.</p>

      <p>Choose the Baseus if you do not need auto-dimming and want to save $84. The asymmetric optics are nearly as good, and you give up only the backlight and the auto-dimming. For most users who work in a room with stable overhead light, the Baseus is the smart pick.</p>

      <p>Choose the Quntis if your budget tops out at $35. It has asymmetric optics, three color temperatures, and stepless dimming. It lacks auto-dimming and the build quality is lighter, but for the price it is remarkable. If you are buying light bars for an entire team, this is the smart pick.</p>

      <p>Check your monitor's bezel thickness before buying. The Halo fits bezels 0.4 to 1.1 inches thick. If your bezel is thinner or thicker, you may need a different mount. If your monitor is curved, most light bars will not work — see our <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-riser-desk/">monitor riser guide</a> for an alternative mounting solution.</p>

      <p>Avoid no-name light bars on Amazon. Several claim "asymmetric optics" but use a flat lens that produces significant screen glare. Stick with BenQ, Baseus, Quntis, or Yeelight. A poorly designed light bar is worse than no light bar, because it adds screen glare without solving the underlying problem.</p>

      <p>Complete your evening work setup with proper ergonomics. The Halo pairs perfectly with blue light glasses (see our <a href="/reviews/best-blue-light-glasses/">guide</a>) and a <a href="/reviews/best-desk-pad-large/">large desk pad</a> for a clean, well-lit workspace that reduces eye strain over long sessions.</p>

